[codex] ## AFTER
[codex] Study 3A
[codex] 
[codex] Participants imagined contributing to a real Facebook campaign advertising popular and inspirational biographical films (ΓÇ£biopicsΓÇ¥). We tested whether feedback about the racial diversity of their initial film selections increased the likelihood that their final selection featured a racial-minority protagonist.
[codex] 
[codex] Methods
[codex] Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/4z8hk), we recruited 1,000 participants on AmazonΓÇÖs MTurk to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (46.1% men; 51.4% women; Mage = 42.20; 72.3% White, 12.0% Black, 6.2% Hispanic, 8.8% Asian).
[codex] Procedure. Participants were truthfully informed about a real Facebook campaign to advertise popular and inspirational biographical films (ΓÇ£biopicsΓÇ¥) and asked to weigh in on which films to include. They saw 25 candidate films, each with a cover-art thumbnail and a brief description listing the protagonistΓÇÖs name (e.g., Judy Garland, Alan Turing), claim to fame (e.g., Actress, WWII codebreaker), release year (e.g., 2019, 2014), and budget (e.g., $10m, $14m); 4 of the 25 films (16%) featured a racial-minority protagonist. Participants selected seven films for the campaign and were told they would receive a $5 bonus if their list was selected in a later vote; after data collection, we chose one participantΓÇÖs list to advertise on Facebook and paid that participant the bonus.
[codex] After their initial selections, participants were randomly assigned to either a no race feedback condition, in which they received descriptive feedback on the percentage of selected films that (1) had a budget above $40M, (2) were released after 2010, and (3) were over 2 hours long, or a race feedback condition, in which they received descriptive feedback on the percentage of selected films featuring a racial-minority protagonist alongside two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the no race feedback attributes. After receiving feedback, participants selected an eighth and final film for the Facebook campaign from the original set, where their prior selections were highlighted. See Materials Section: Study 3A in the Appendix for complete study materials.
[codex] 
[codex] Results
[codex] Initial selections featured racial-minority protagonists 16.1% of the time, with balance across conditions (16.6% in the no race feedback condition vs. 15.8% in the race feedback condition, p = .314; see Appendix Table S3). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors predicting whether the eighth and final biopic selected featured a racial-minority protagonist, using assignment to the race feedback condition as the primary predictor. As shown in Figure S2A and Model 1 of Table S3, participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a racial-minority protagonist in the race feedback condition (27.10% chose a biopic featuring a racial-minority protagonist) than in the no race feedback condition (17.73% chose a biopic featuring a racial-minority protagonist; B = 0.094, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.145], t(998) = 3.57, p < .001).
[codex] As shown in Figure S2A and Table S3 (Models 5-8), and as predicted, the effect of assignment to the race feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting an eighth and final film with a racial-minority protagonist was larger than the effect of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of initial films selected with a (1) budget above $40M (F(1, 1992) = 7.71, p = .006), (2) release year after 2010 (F(1, 1992) = 13.74, p < .001), or (3) average duration of over two hours (F(1, 1992) = 6.92, p = .009) on subsequent selections of an eighth and final biopic with, respectively, a (1) budget above $40M, (2) release year after 2010, or (3) average duration of over two hours.
